<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="9" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="8.[264,1324,1255,1762]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,389,1575,1601]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Notes.</emphasis>
Representatives of several other species are in the 
<collectionCode box="[1022,1112,1576,1602]" httpUri="http://grbio.org/cool/142r-0w94" name="Smithsonian Institution, National Museum of Natural History" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">NMNH</collectionCode>
collections; their elytral markings are different, or they have rufous head and pronotum rather than piceous as in the present species, and they are all fully winged. A monographic revision of this group is necessary and will likely be scientifically rewarding because of the wingless state of this species and the association with 
<taxonomicName box="[727,775,1736,1761]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Atta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[727,775,1736,1761]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Atta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
ants of other species.
</paragraph>
